#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:422
msgid "setup/teardown"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:424
msgid ""
"One thing that might catch users by surprise is that plain ``setup`` and "
"``teardown`` methods are not pytest native, they are in fact part of the "
"``nose`` support."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:428
msgid ""
"class Test:\n"
"    def setup(self):\n"
"        self.resource = make_resource()\n"
"\n"
"    def teardown(self):\n"
"        self.resource.close()\n"
"\n"
"    def test_foo(self): ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_bar(self): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:443
msgid ""
"Native pytest support uses ``setup_method`` and ``teardown_method`` (see :"
"ref:`xunit-method-setup`), so the above should be changed to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:445
msgid ""
"class Test:\n"
"    def setup_method(self):\n"
"        self.resource = make_resource()\n"
"\n"
"    def teardown_method(self):\n"
"        self.resource.close()\n"
"\n"
"    def test_foo(self): ...\n"
"\n"
"    def test_bar(self): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:459
msgid ""
"This is easy to do in an entire code base by doing a simple find/replace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:462
msgid "@with_setup"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:464
msgid "Code using `@with_setup <with-setup-nose>`_ such as this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:466
msgid ""
"from nose.tools import with_setup\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def setup_some_resource(): ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def teardown_some_resource(): ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@with_setup(setup_some_resource, teardown_some_resource)\n"
"def test_foo(): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:480
msgid ""
"Will also need to be ported to a supported pytest style. One way to do it is "
"using a fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:482
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def setup_some_resource(): ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def teardown_some_resource(): ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def some_resource():\n"
"    setup_some_resource()\n"
"    yield\n"
"    teardown_some_resource()\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_foo(some_resource): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:507
msgid "The ``compat_co_firstlineno`` attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:509
msgid ""
"Nose inspects this attribute on function objects to allow overriding the "
"function's inferred line number. Pytest no longer respects this attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:515
msgid "Passing ``msg=`` to ``pytest.skip``, ``pytest.fail`` or ``pytest.exit``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:520
msgid ""
"Passing the keyword argument ``msg`` to :func:`pytest.skip`, :func:`pytest."
"fail` or :func:`pytest.exit` is now deprecated and ``reason`` should be used "
"instead.  This change is to bring consistency between these functions and "
"the ``@pytest.mark.skip`` and ``@pytest.mark.xfail`` markers which already "
"accept a ``reason`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:524
msgid ""
"def test_fail_example():\n"
"    # old\n"
"    pytest.fail(msg=\"foo\")\n"
"    # new\n"
"    pytest.fail(reason=\"bar\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_skip_example():\n"
"    # old\n"
"    pytest.skip(msg=\"foo\")\n"
"    # new\n"
"    pytest.skip(reason=\"bar\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_exit_example():\n"
"    # old\n"
"    pytest.exit(msg=\"foo\")\n"
"    # new\n"
"    pytest.exit(reason=\"bar\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:550
msgid "The ``pytest.Instance`` collector"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:554
msgid "The ``pytest.Instance`` collector type has been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:556
msgid ""
"Previously, Python test methods were collected as :class:`~pytest.Class` -> "
"``Instance`` -> :class:`~pytest.Function`. Now :class:`~pytest.Class` "
"collects the test methods directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:559
msgid ""
"Most plugins which reference ``Instance`` do so in order to ignore or skip "
"it, using a check such as ``if isinstance(node, Instance): return``. Such "
"plugins should simply remove consideration of ``Instance`` on pytest>=7. "
"However, to keep such uses working, a dummy type has been instanced in "
"``pytest.Instance`` and ``_pytest.python.Instance``, and importing it emits "
"a deprecation warning. This was removed in pytest 8."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:567
msgid "Using ``pytest.warns(None)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:572
msgid ""
":func:`pytest.warns(None) <pytest.warns>` is now deprecated because it was "
"frequently misused. Its correct usage was checking that the code emits at "
"least one warning of any type - like ``pytest.warns()`` or ``pytest."
"warns(Warning)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:576
msgid "See :ref:`warns use cases` for examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:580
msgid "Backward compatibilities in ``Parser.addoption``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:585
msgid ""
"Several behaviors of :meth:`Parser.addoption <pytest.Parser.addoption>` are "
"now removed in pytest 8 (deprecated since pytest 2.4.0):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:588
msgid ""
"``parser.addoption(..., help=\".. %default ..\")`` - use ``%(default)s`` "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:589
msgid ""
"``parser.addoption(..., type=\"int/string/float/complex\")`` - use "
"``type=int`` etc. instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:593
msgid "The ``--strict`` command-line option (reintroduced)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:598
msgid ""
"The ``--strict`` command-line option had been deprecated in favor of ``--"
"strict-markers``, which better conveys what the option does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:601
msgid "In version 8.1, we accidentally un-deprecated ``--strict``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:603
msgid ""
"In version 9.0, we changed ``--strict`` to make it set the new :confval:"
"`strict` configuration option. It now enables all strictness related options "
"(including :confval:`strict_markers`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:611
msgid "Implementing the ``pytest_cmdline_preparse`` hook"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:616
msgid ""
"Implementing the ``pytest_cmdline_preparse`` hook has been officially "
"deprecated. Implement the :hook:`pytest_load_initial_conftests` hook instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:619
msgid ""
"def pytest_cmdline_preparse(config: Config, args: List[str]) -> None: ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"# becomes:\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_load_initial_conftests(\n"
"    early_config: Config, parser: Parser, args: List[str]\n"
") -> None: ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:633
msgid "Collection changes in pytest 8"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:635
msgid ""
"Added a new :class:`pytest.Directory` base collection node, which all "
"collector nodes for filesystem directories are expected to subclass. This is "
"analogous to the existing :class:`pytest.File` for file nodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:638
msgid ""
"Changed :class:`pytest.Package` to be a subclass of :class:`pytest."
"Directory`. A ``Package`` represents a filesystem directory which is a "
"Python package, i.e. contains an ``__init__.py`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:642
msgid ""
":class:`pytest.Package` now only collects files in its own directory; "
"previously it collected recursively. Sub-directories are collected as sub-"
"collector nodes, thus creating a collection tree which mirrors the "
"filesystem hierarchy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:645
msgid ""
":attr:`session.name <pytest.Session.name>` is now ``\"\"``; previously it "
"was the rootdir directory name. This matches :attr:`session.nodeid <_pytest."
"nodes.Node.nodeid>` which has always been `\"\"`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:648
msgid ""
"Added a new :class:`pytest.Dir` concrete collection node, a subclass of :"
"class:`pytest.Directory`. This node represents a filesystem directory, which "
"is not a :class:`pytest.Package`, i.e. does not contain an ``__init__.py`` "
"file. Similarly to ``Package``, it only collects the files in its own "
"directory, while collecting sub-directories as sub-collector nodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:654
msgid ""
"Files and directories are now collected in alphabetical order jointly, "
"unless changed by a plugin. Previously, files were collected before "
"directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:657
msgid ""
"The collection tree now contains directories/packages up to the :ref:"
"`rootdir <rootdir>`, for initial arguments that are found within the "
"rootdir. For files outside the rootdir, only the immediate directory/package "
"is collected -- note however that collecting from outside the rootdir is "
"discouraged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:662
msgid "As an example, given the following filesystem tree::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:664
msgid ""
"myroot/\n"
"    pytest.ini\n"
"    top/\n"
"    ├── aaa\n"
"    │   └── test_aaa.py\n"
"    ├── test_a.py\n"
"    ├── test_b\n"
"    │   ├── __init__.py\n"
"    │   └── test_b.py\n"
"    ├── test_c.py\n"
"    └── zzz\n"
"        ├── __init__.py\n"
"        └── test_zzz.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:678
msgid ""
"the collection tree, as shown by `pytest --collect-only top/` but with the "
"otherwise-hidden :class:`~pytest.Session` node added for clarity, is now the "
"following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:681
msgid ""
"<Session>\n"
"  <Dir myroot>\n"
"    <Dir top>\n"
"      <Dir aaa>\n"
"        <Module test_aaa.py>\n"
"          <Function test_it>\n"
"      <Module test_a.py>\n"
"        <Function test_it>\n"
"      <Package test_b>\n"
"        <Module test_b.py>\n"
"          <Function test_it>\n"
"      <Module test_c.py>\n"
"        <Function test_it>\n"
"      <Package zzz>\n"
"        <Module test_zzz.py>\n"
"          <Function test_it>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:698
msgid "Previously, it was::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:700
msgid ""
"<Session>\n"
"  <Module top/test_a.py>\n"
"    <Function test_it>\n"
"  <Module top/test_c.py>\n"
"    <Function test_it>\n"
"  <Module top/aaa/test_aaa.py>\n"
"    <Function test_it>\n"
"  <Package test_b>\n"
"    <Module test_b.py>\n"
"      <Function test_it>\n"
"  <Package zzz>\n"
"    <Module test_zzz.py>\n"
"      <Function test_it>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:714
msgid ""
"Code/plugins which rely on a specific shape of the collection tree might "
"need to update."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:718
msgid ""
":class:`pytest.Package` is no longer a :class:`pytest.Module` or :class:"
"`pytest.File`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:722
msgid ""
"The ``Package`` collector node designates a Python package, that is, a "
"directory with an `__init__.py` file. Previously ``Package`` was a subtype "
"of ``pytest.Module`` (which represents a single Python module), the module "
"being the `__init__.py` file. This has been deemed a design mistake (see :"
"issue:`11137` and :issue:`7777` for details)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:727
msgid ""
"The ``path`` property of ``Package`` nodes now points to the package "
"directory instead of the ``__init__.py`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:729
msgid ""
"Note that a ``Module`` node for ``__init__.py`` (which is not a ``Package``) "
"may still exist, if it is picked up during collection (e.g. if you "
"configured :confval:`python_files` to include ``__init__.py`` files)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:734
msgid "Collecting ``__init__.py`` files no longer collects package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:738
msgid ""
"Running `pytest pkg/__init__.py` now collects the `pkg/__init__.py` file "
"(module) only. Previously, it collected the entire `pkg` package, including "
"other test files in the directory, but excluding tests in the `__init__.py` "
"file itself (unless :confval:`python_files` was changed to allow `__init__."
"py` file)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:742
msgid ""
"To collect the entire package, specify just the directory: `pytest pkg`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:746
msgid "The ``pytest.collect`` module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:751
msgid ""
"The ``pytest.collect`` module is no longer part of the public API, all its "
"names should now be imported from ``pytest`` directly instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:757
msgid "The ``pytest_warning_captured`` hook"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:762
msgid ""
"This hook has an `item` parameter which cannot be serialized by ``pytest-"
"xdist``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:764
msgid ""
"Use the ``pytest_warning_recorded`` hook instead, which replaces the "
"``item`` parameter by a ``nodeid`` parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:770
msgid "The ``pytest._fillfuncargs`` function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:775
msgid "This function was kept for backward compatibility with an older plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:777
msgid ""
"Its functionality is not meant to be used directly, but if you must replace "
"it, use `function._request._fillfixtures()` instead, though note this is not "
"a public API and may break in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:783
msgid "``--no-print-logs`` command-line option"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:789
msgid ""
"The ``--no-print-logs`` option and ``log_print`` ini setting are removed. If "
"you used them, please use ``--show-capture`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:792
msgid ""
"A ``--show-capture`` command-line option was added in ``pytest 3.5.0`` which "
"allows to specify how to display captured output when tests fail: ``no``, "
"``stdout``, ``stderr``, ``log`` or ``all`` (the default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:799
msgid "Result log (``--result-log``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:804
msgid ""
"The ``--result-log`` option produces a stream of test reports which can be "
"analysed at runtime, but it uses a custom format which requires users to "
"implement their own parser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:808
msgid ""
"The :pypi:`pytest-reportlog` plugin provides a ``--report-log`` option, a "
"more standard and extensible alternative, producing one JSON object per-"
"line, and should cover the same use cases. Please try it out and provide "
"feedback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:811
msgid ""
"The ``pytest-reportlog`` plugin might even be merged into the core at some "
"point, depending on the plans for the plugins and number of users using it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:815
msgid "``pytest_collect_directory`` hook"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:819
msgid ""
"The ``pytest_collect_directory`` hook has not worked properly for years (it "
"was called but the results were ignored). Users may consider using :hook:"
"`pytest_collection_modifyitems` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:823
msgid "TerminalReporter.writer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:827
msgid ""
"The ``TerminalReporter.writer`` attribute has been deprecated and should no "
"longer be used. This was inadvertently exposed as part of the public API of "
"that plugin and ties it too much with ``py.io.TerminalWriter``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:831
msgid ""
"Plugins that used ``TerminalReporter.writer`` directly should instead use "
"``TerminalReporter`` methods that provide the same functionality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:837
msgid "``junit_family`` default value change to \"xunit2\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:841
msgid ""
"The default value of ``junit_family`` option will change to ``xunit2`` in "
"pytest 6.0, which is an update of the old ``xunit1`` format and is supported "
"by default in modern tools that manipulate this type of file (for example, "
"Jenkins, Azure Pipelines, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:845
msgid ""
"Users are recommended to try the new ``xunit2`` format and see if their "
"tooling that consumes the JUnit XML file supports it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:848
msgid "To use the new format, update your configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:852
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_family = \"xunit2\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:859
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_family = xunit2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:864
msgid ""
"If you discover that your tooling does not support the new format, and want "
"to keep using the legacy version, set the option to ``legacy`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:869
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_family = \"legacy\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:876
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_family = legacy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:881
msgid ""
"By using ``legacy`` you will keep using the legacy/xunit1 format when "
"upgrading to pytest 6.0, where the default format will be ``xunit2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:884
msgid ""
"In order to let users know about the transition, pytest will issue a warning "
"in case the ``--junit-xml`` option is given in the command line but "
"``junit_family`` is not explicitly configured in ``pytest.ini``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:888
msgid "Services known to support the ``xunit2`` format:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:890
msgid ""
"`Jenkins <https://www.jenkins.io/>`__ with the `JUnit <https://plugins."
"jenkins.io/junit>`__ plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:891
msgid ""
"`Azure Pipelines <https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/services/devops/"
"pipelines>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:894
msgid "Node Construction changed to ``Node.from_parent``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:898
msgid ""
"The construction of nodes now should use the named constructor "
"``from_parent``. This limitation in api surface intends to enable better/"
"simpler refactoring of the collection tree."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:901
msgid ""
"This means that instead of :code:`MyItem(name=\"foo\", parent=collector, "
"obj=42)` one now has to invoke :code:`MyItem.from_parent(collector, "
"name=\"foo\")`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:904
msgid ""
"Plugins that wish to support older versions of pytest and suppress the "
"warning can use `hasattr` to check if `from_parent` exists in that version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:907
msgid ""
"def pytest_pycollect_makeitem(collector, name, obj):\n"
"    if hasattr(MyItem, \"from_parent\"):\n"
"        item = MyItem.from_parent(collector, name=\"foo\")\n"
"        item.obj = 42\n"
"        return item\n"
"    else:\n"
"        return MyItem(name=\"foo\", parent=collector, obj=42)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:917
msgid ""
"Note that ``from_parent`` should only be called with keyword arguments for "
"the parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:921
msgid "``pytest.fixture`` arguments are keyword only"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:925
msgid ""
"Passing arguments to pytest.fixture() as positional arguments has been "
"removed - pass them by keyword instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:928
msgid "``funcargnames`` alias for ``fixturenames``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:932
msgid ""
"The ``FixtureRequest``, ``Metafunc``, and ``Function`` classes track the "
"names of their associated fixtures, with the aptly-named ``fixturenames`` "
"attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:935
msgid ""
"Prior to pytest 2.3, this attribute was named ``funcargnames``, and we have "
"kept that as an alias since.  It is finally due for removal, as it is often "
"confusing in places where we or plugin authors must distinguish between "
"fixture names and names supplied by non-fixture things such as ``pytest.mark."
"parametrize``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:944
msgid "``pytest.config`` global"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:948
msgid ""
"The ``pytest.config`` global object is deprecated.  Instead use ``request."
"config`` (via the ``request`` fixture) or if you are a plugin author use the "
"``pytest_configure(config)`` hook. Note that many hooks can also access the "
"``config`` object indirectly, through ``session.config`` or ``item.config`` "
"for example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:957
msgid "``\"message\"`` parameter of ``pytest.raises``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:961
msgid ""
"It is a common mistake to think this parameter will match the exception "
"message, while in fact it only serves to provide a custom message in case "
"the ``pytest.raises`` check fails. To prevent users from making this "
"mistake, and because it is believed to be little used, pytest is deprecating "
"it without providing an alternative for the moment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:966
msgid ""
"If you have a valid use case for this parameter, consider that to obtain the "
"same results you can just call ``pytest.fail`` manually at the end of the "
"``with`` statement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:969 ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1278
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:971
msgid ""
"with pytest.raises(TimeoutError, message=\"Client got unexpected "
"message\"):\n"
"    wait_for(websocket.recv(), 0.5)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:977 ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1010
#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1139 ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1209
msgid "Becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:979
msgid ""
"with pytest.raises(TimeoutError):\n"
"    wait_for(websocket.recv(), 0.5)\n"
"    pytest.fail(\"Client got unexpected message\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:986
msgid ""
"If you still have concerns about this deprecation and future removal, please "
"comment on :issue:`3974`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:993
msgid "``raises`` / ``warns`` with a string as the second argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:997
msgid ""
"Use the context manager form of these instead.  When necessary, invoke "
"``exec`` directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1000 ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1131
#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1156
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1002
msgid ""
"pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError, \"1 / 0\")\n"
"pytest.raises(SyntaxError, \"a $ b\")\n"
"\n"
"pytest.warns(DeprecationWarning, \"my_function()\")\n"
"pytest.warns(SyntaxWarning, \"assert(1, 2)\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1012
msgid ""
"with pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError):\n"
"    1 / 0\n"
"with pytest.raises(SyntaxError):\n"
"    exec(\"a $ b\")  # exec is required for invalid syntax\n"
"\n"
"with pytest.warns(DeprecationWarning):\n"
"    my_function()\n"
"with pytest.warns(SyntaxWarning):\n"
"    exec(\"assert(1, 2)\")  # exec is used to avoid a top-level warning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1028
msgid "Using ``Class`` in custom Collectors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1032
msgid ""
"Using objects named ``\"Class\"`` as a way to customize the type of nodes "
"that are collected in ``Collector`` subclasses has been deprecated. Users "
"instead should use ``pytest_pycollect_makeitem`` to customize node types "
"during collection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1036
msgid ""
"This issue should affect only advanced plugins who create new collection "
"types, so if you see this warning message please contact the authors so they "
"can change the code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1043
msgid "marks in ``pytest.mark.parametrize``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1047
msgid ""
"Applying marks to values of a ``pytest.mark.parametrize`` call is now "
"deprecated. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1049
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n"
"    \"a, b\",\n"
"    [\n"
"        (3, 9),\n"
"        pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"flaky\")(6, 36),\n"
"        (10, 100),\n"
"        (20, 200),\n"
"        (40, 400),\n"
"        (50, 500),\n"
"    ],\n"
")\n"
"def test_foo(a, b): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1064
msgid ""
"This code applies the ``pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"flaky\")`` mark to the "
"``(6, 36)`` value of the above parametrization call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1067
msgid ""
"This was considered hard to read and understand, and also its implementation "
"presented problems to the code preventing further internal improvements in "
"the marks architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1070
msgid "To update the code, use ``pytest.param``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1072
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n"
"    \"a, b\",\n"
"    [\n"
"        (3, 9),\n"
"        pytest.param(6, 36, marks=pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"flaky\")),\n"
"        (10, 100),\n"
"        (20, 200),\n"
"        (40, 400),\n"
"        (50, 500),\n"
"    ],\n"
")\n"
"def test_foo(a, b): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1091
msgid "``pytest_funcarg__`` prefix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1095
msgid ""
"In very early pytest versions fixtures could be defined using the "
"``pytest_funcarg__`` prefix:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1097
msgid ""
"def pytest_funcarg__data():\n"
"    return SomeData()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1102
msgid "Switch over to the ``@pytest.fixture`` decorator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1104
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def data():\n"
"    return SomeData()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1113
msgid "[pytest] section in setup.cfg files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1117
msgid ""
"``[pytest]`` sections in ``setup.cfg`` files should now be named ``[tool:"
"pytest]`` to avoid conflicts with other distutils commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1124
msgid "Metafunc.addcall"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1128
msgid ""
"``Metafunc.addcall`` was a precursor to the current parametrized mechanism. "
"Users should use :meth:`pytest.Metafunc.parametrize` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1133
msgid ""
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    metafunc.addcall({\"i\": 1}, id=\"1\")\n"
"    metafunc.addcall({\"i\": 2}, id=\"2\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1141
msgid ""
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    metafunc.parametrize(\"i\", [1, 2], ids=[\"1\", \"2\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1150
msgid "``cached_setup``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1154
msgid ""
"``request.cached_setup`` was the precursor of the setup/teardown mechanism "
"available to fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1158
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def db_session():\n"
"    return request.cached_setup(\n"
"        setup=Session.create, teardown=lambda session: session.close(), "
"scope=\"module\"\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1166
msgid "This should be updated to make use of standard fixture mechanisms:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1168
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def db_session():\n"
"    session = Session.create()\n"
"    yield session\n"
"    session.close()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1177
msgid ""
"You can consult :std:doc:`funcarg comparison section in the docs "
"<funcarg_compare>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1184
msgid "pytest_plugins in non-top-level conftest files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1188
msgid ""
"Defining :globalvar:`pytest_plugins` is now deprecated in non-top-level "
"conftest.py files because they will activate referenced plugins *globally*, "
"which is surprising because for all other pytest features ``conftest.py`` "
"files are only *active* for tests at or below it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1196
msgid "``Config.warn`` and ``Node.warn``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1200
msgid ""
"Those methods were part of the internal pytest warnings system, but since "
"``3.8`` pytest is using the builtin warning system for its own warnings, so "
"those two functions are now deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1203
msgid ""
"``Config.warn`` should be replaced by calls to the standard ``warnings."
"warn``, example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1205
msgid "config.warn(\"C1\", \"some warning\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1211
msgid "warnings.warn(pytest.PytestWarning(\"some warning\"))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1215
msgid "``Node.warn`` now supports two signatures:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1217
msgid ""
"``node.warn(PytestWarning(\"some message\"))``: is now the **recommended** "
"way to call this function. The warning instance must be a PytestWarning or "
"subclass."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1220
msgid ""
"``node.warn(\"CI\", \"some message\")``: this code/message form has been "
"**removed** and should be converted to the warning instance form above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1225
msgid "record_xml_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1229
msgid ""
"The ``record_xml_property`` fixture is now deprecated in favor of the more "
"generic ``record_property``, which can be used by other consumers (for "
"example ``pytest-html``) to obtain custom information about the test run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1232
msgid "This is just a matter of renaming the fixture as the API is the same:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1234
msgid "def test_foo(record_xml_property): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1238
msgid "Change to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1240
msgid "def test_foo(record_property): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1248
msgid "Passing command-line string to ``pytest.main()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1252
msgid "Passing a command-line string to ``pytest.main()`` is deprecated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1254
msgid "pytest.main(\"-v -s\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1258
msgid "Pass a list instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1260
msgid "pytest.main([\"-v\", \"-s\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1265
msgid ""
"By passing a string, users expect that pytest will interpret that command-"
"line using the shell rules they are working on (for example ``bash`` or "
"``Powershell``), but this is very hard/impossible to do in a portable way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1272
msgid "Calling fixtures directly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1276
msgid ""
"Calling a fixture function directly, as opposed to request them in a test "
"function, is deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1280
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def cell():\n"
"    return ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def full_cell():\n"
"    cell = cell()\n"
"    cell.make_full()\n"
"    return cell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1293
msgid ""
"This is a great source of confusion to new users, which will often call the "
"fixture functions and request them from test functions interchangeably, "
"which breaks the fixture resolution model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1295
msgid ""
"In those cases just request the function directly in the dependent fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1297
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def cell():\n"
"    return ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def full_cell(cell):\n"
"    cell.make_full()\n"
"    return cell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1309
msgid ""
"Alternatively if the fixture function is called multiple times inside a test "
"(making it hard to apply the above pattern) or if you would like to make "
"minimal changes to the code, you can create a fixture which calls the "
"original function together with the ``name`` parameter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1313
msgid ""
"def cell():\n"
"    return ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(name=\"cell\")\n"
"def cell_fixture():\n"
"    return cell()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1327
msgid "Internal classes accessed through ``Node``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1331
msgid ""
"Access of ``Module``, ``Function``, ``Class``, ``Instance``, ``File`` and "
"``Item`` through ``Node`` instances now issue this warning:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1334
msgid ""
"usage of Function.Module is deprecated, please use pytest.Module instead"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1338
msgid ""
"Users should just ``import pytest`` and access those objects using the "
"``pytest`` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1340
msgid ""
"This has been documented as deprecated for years, but only now we are "
"actually emitting deprecation warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1343
msgid "``Node.get_marker``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1347
msgid ""
"As part of a large :ref:`marker-revamp`, ``_pytest.nodes.Node.get_marker`` "
"is removed. See :ref:`the documentation <update marker code>` on tips on how "
"to update your code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1352
msgid "``somefunction.markname``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1356
msgid ""
"As part of a large :ref:`marker-revamp` we already deprecated using "
"``MarkInfo`` the only correct way to get markers of an element is via ``node."
"iter_markers(name)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1363
msgid "``pytest_namespace``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1367
msgid ""
"This hook is deprecated because it greatly complicates the pytest internals "
"regarding configuration and initialization, making some bug fixes and "
"refactorings impossible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1370
msgid "Example of usage:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1372
msgid ""
"class MySymbol: ...\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_namespace():\n"
"    return {\"my_symbol\": MySymbol()}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1381
msgid ""
"Plugin authors relying on this hook should instead require that users now "
"import the plugin modules directly (with an appropriate public API)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1383
msgid ""
"As a stopgap measure, plugin authors may still inject their names into "
"pytest's namespace, usually during ``pytest_configure``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/deprecations.rst:1385
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_configure():\n"
"    pytest.my_symbol = MySymbol()"
msgstr ""
